tspan.tspan: Reduce the target principality's province count by one and increase
your province count by one.
Reduce their up to 2 provinces without one from the unaligned
Principality or the Player and his allies.
For every province you take lose 1 Diplomatic Influence somewhere
on the board or from your stored Influence unless you are the
Emperor taking from a Foreign Power.
Take up to one adjacent province per vassal from the unaligned
Principality or the Player and his vassals. Lose 2 Diplomatic Influence
from each of your allies that could have conquered a province but did
not.
Lose all Diplomatic Influence with a Principality if you personally (not
an vassal) take a province from them. Remove all Diplomatic
Influence from conquered Principalities.
Choose whether to immediately vassalize a Principality (or former
Player-owned capital) instead of conquering it.
To vassalize, keep the Principality's control marker on province (or
replace the Player's with a new Principality control marker). Lose no
Diplomatic Influence when vassalizing. Instead, remove all
Diplomatic Influence of other Players from the Principality and place
enough Diplomatic Influence on it to become its suzereign.
Electors cannot lose their last province but they can be vassalized.
If a Principality conquers a province of a different religion, that
province is forcibly converted to the Principality's religion (No Saints/
Reformation Points earned).
Defeat:
If you lose to an unaligned Principality, it conquers two (but not your
last) provinces of your choice from you and/or your vassals. The
provinces need not be adjacent to the unaligned Principality.
If you run out of provinces then you become a Foreign Power if you
are not already one.
Lose 2 Diplomatic Influence with each of your allies per province
they lost.
